article.description:
Richard Hamilton scored 26 points and
Ben Wallace pulled down 20 rebounds as the Detroit Pistons routed
the Chicago Bulls 105-82 Sunday.
article.headline: Hamilton, Wallace power Pistons past Bulls
article.linkText: Wallace, Pistons continue mastery of lowly Bulls
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The way Ben Wallace is playing, the worst thing to do is fire him up.
Wallace

That apparently didn't occur to injured Chicago Bulls forward Marcus Fizer, who got into a shouting match with Wallace and Corliss Williamson at the end of the first quarter Sunday. Wallace finished with 20 rebounds, seven points, five blocks and four steals as the Pistons routed the Bulls 105-82. "That didn't bother me -- it was just some guy trying to be tough with a pink tie on,'' Wallace said. "One of their guys tripped me, and I went over to say something about it, and that guy started yelling at me about being in their huddle. I didn't worry about it -- we were just taking care of business.'' Wallace is averaging 20.6 rebounds in Detroit's last eight games. "You take him away from the Pistons, and I'm pretty sure they aren't the best team in the East,'' said Jalen Rose. "If you go by what he does for a team and what he has done for the league, from a rebounding standpoint, from having a good attitude, playing hard, stealing the ball and being a consummate teammate, then he wins the MVP hands down.'' The Pistons are 3-0 against the Bulls this season, and have won 17 of 19 meetings since Michael Jordan left Chicago. The victory increased Detroit's Central Division lead to 3{ games over idle Indiana. "We know that if we want to stay in first place, we can't underestimate anyone,'' said Richard Hamilton, who led the Pistons with 26 points. "We got a lot of easy baskets in transition, and when we do that, our offense is going to be smooth.'' Chicago was missing Donyell Marshall, its leading rebounder and second-leading scorer, after he injured his ribs in Saturday's win over New York. The Bulls have lost seven straight on the road and have just three wins away from Chicago all season. "It's frustrating,'' said Eddy Curry, who led the Bulls with 18. "It gets real frustrating to know that we're making it harder than it has to be to win a game on the road. A lot of teams that we can at least contain somewhat at home are blowing us out on the road.'' Chauncey Billups added 16 points for the Pistons, while Cliff Robinson and Mehmet Okur had 13 each. "With a team like that, if you get into their kind of game, they have enough talent to beat you,'' Wallace said. "Atlanta is coming here next, and they are the same way. We just have to stay calm and play our game.'' Rose had six on 3-for-15 shooting, just his second single-digit scoring effort in 101 games with the Bulls. "It happens to the best of us,'' Rose said. "They are the best team in the East and, obviously, we are horrible on the road.'' Detroit led 49-43 at the half, thanks to 11 points from Okur, and Hamilton had seven points in a 13-4 run to start the second half, moving the lead to 62-47. The Pistons scored 33 points in the quarter and led by as many as 26. The margin was 82-62 at the end of the period, and Chicago never threatened in the fourth. "I thought Chicago played really tough in the first half, but we were able to get some stops and hit some shots in the second half and open it up a little,'' Pistons coach Rick Carlisle said. "We made some adjustments and made it tough on them.'' Game notes
A broken lock kept the referees out of their dressing room for most of the intermission. ... Pistons guard Chucky Atkins missed the game with a bruised knee. ... Pistons guard Chauncey Billups had "God Bless the Soldiers'' written on his shoes. ... The Pistons had their sellout streak broken at seven games, but still drew 20,415 fans. ... The Bulls had just one steal in the game, coming when Jay Williams intercepted Okur's pass in the second quarter.
